            </font></Label>
        <Label id="content1" text="• It’s an idealized model which is assumed to have a perfectly definite and unchanging shape and size.&#13;&#13;• Any activity that requires muscular or mental effort.&#13;&#13;• It is one where all particles maintain their relative position (as the body rotates, all particles move but relative positions don't change.&#13;&#13;• Rotational Kinematics - describes the rotational motion." textAlignment="CENTER" wrapText="true">
            <font>
                <Font name="Century Gothic" size="12.0" />
            </font></Label>
        <Label id="subtitle2" text="Angular Velocity and Acceleration" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrapText="true">
            <font>
                <Font name="Century Gothic Bold" size="15.0" />
            </font></Label>
        <Label id="content2" text="• Fixed Axis - an object that spins in the same place. (xy-plane)&#13;○ e.g. - objects on the rim of the tire go around the same place over and over again.&#13;&#13;• Angular Coordinate - The angular coordinate of a rigid body can be positive (+) or negative (-).&#13;○ Counter-clockwise direction from x-axis = (+)&#13;○ Clockwise direction from x-axis = (-)&#13;&#13;• Units of Angles&#13;○ When measuring angles, Radians are more naturally used compared to degrees.&#13;○ 1 rad = angle subtended at the center of a circle by an arc with a length equal to the radius of the circle.&#13;○ One complete revolution is 360° = 2π radians.&#13;&#13;• Angular Velocity&#13;○ The angular velocity can be positive or negative, depending on the direction in which the rigid body is rotating.&#13;○ Angular speed is the magnitude of angular velocity (never negative).&#13;○ At any instance, every part of a rotating rigid body has the same angular velocity.&#13;○ Angular velocity is defined as a vector whose direction is given by the right-hand rule.&#13;&#13;• Angular Acceleration&#13;○ A rigid body whose angular velocity changes has an angular acceleration.&#13;○ Usual unit is rad/s^2" textAlignment="CENTER" wrapText="true">
            <font>
                <Font name="Century Gothic" size="12.0" />
            </font></Label>
